This project is a **Next.js 14 school website**. We created it so the site has three main layers working together:

1. **Public website UI**
2. **Admin/dashboard area**
3. **Backend/API + database models**

Here’s what each folder and key file does.

**Root Level**

`app/`
This is the heart of the website in Next.js App Router.
Everything the user visits in the browser lives here.
It contains:
- Public pages like Home, About, Contact, Gallery
- Admin pages like `/admin/dashboard`
- API routes like `/api/notices` and `/api/contact`
- Global layout and global CSS

`components/`
Reusable UI pieces.
Instead of repeating the same header, footer, cards, forms, or admin shell everywhere, we created them once here and reused them across pages.

`lib/`
Shared logic and utilities.
This is where we put:
- MongoDB connection code
- auth config
- helper functions
- sample data
- content loaders
- YouTube URL parsing logic

`models/`
MongoDB/Mongoose schemas.
Each file defines the structure of one collection in the database, like notices, downloads, gallery items, contact messages, and site settings.

`scripts/`
Helper scripts for development tasks.
Right now it contains the seed script to insert sample data into MongoDB.

`.env.example`
A template showing which environment variables the project needs, like:
- `MONGODB_URI`
- `NEXTAUTH_SECRET`
- `NEXTAUTH_URL`
- `ADMIN_USERNAME`
- `ADMIN_PASSWORD`

`.gitignore`
Tells Git which files/folders not to track, like `node_modules`, `.next`, `.env`.

`package.json`
Project manifest.
Defines:
- project name
- dependencies
- scripts like `npm run dev`, `npm run build`, `npm run seed`

`tsconfig.json`
TypeScript configuration.

`tailwind.config.ts`
Tailwind design setup.
This is where we defined the school theme colors like:
- blue `#0F4C81`
- saffron `#FF9933`
- green `#138808`

`postcss.config.js`
Supports Tailwind CSS processing.

`next.config.js`
Next.js configuration.
We used it mainly to allow remote images.

`middleware.ts`
Protects admin routes using NextAuth middleware.

`README.md`
Setup notes and project overview.

**Inside `app/`**

`app/layout.tsx`
Global layout for the whole site.
It loads:
- fonts
- metadata
- global CSS

Every page is wrapped through this layout.

`app/globals.css`
Global styles used across the entire website.

`app/page.tsx`
Homepage.
This page includes the main school landing UI:
- hero section
- principal message
- why choose us
- facilities preview
- latest notices
- events
- gallery
- downloads
- contact/map preview

`app/about/page.tsx`
About school page.

`app/academics/page.tsx`
Academics page.

`app/admissions/page.tsx`
Admissions page.

`app/facilities/page.tsx`
Facilities page.

`app/activities/page.tsx`
Student activities and achievements page.

`app/notices/page.tsx`
Shows all public notices.

`app/gallery/page.tsx`
Shows gallery photos and videos.

`app/downloads/page.tsx`
Shows downloadable documents like forms and circulars.

`app/disclosure/page.tsx`
Mandatory public disclosure page.

`app/contact/page.tsx`
Contact page with office details, map, and form.

**Inside `app/admin/`**

This is the admin area UI.

`app/admin/page.tsx`
Admin login page.

`app/admin/dashboard/page.tsx`
Admin overview page.

`app/admin/notices/page.tsx`
UI for managing notices.

`app/admin/gallery/page.tsx`
UI for managing gallery content.

`app/admin/downloads/page.tsx`
UI for managing downloadable documents.

`app/admin/homepage/page.tsx`
UI placeholder for editing homepage content.

`app/admin/settings/page.tsx`
UI placeholder for site-wide settings like school name, address, map, contact info.

Important note:
These admin pages are currently **scaffolded UI**. The structure is ready, but the forms are not fully wired to save live content from the browser yet.

**Inside `app/api/`**

This is the backend API layer.

`app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`
Handles admin authentication through NextAuth.

`app/api/notices/route.ts`
Public `GET` for notices and admin `POST` for creating notices.

`app/api/notices/[id]/route.ts`
Single notice actions:
- `GET`
- `PUT`
- `DELETE`

`app/api/gallery/route.ts`
Gallery list and create route.

`app/api/gallery/[id]/route.ts`
Delete gallery item.

`app/api/downloads/route.ts`
Downloads list and create route.

`app/api/downloads/[id]/route.ts`
Delete download item.

`app/api/homepage/route.ts`
Get and update homepage content.

`app/api/settings/route.ts`
Get and update site settings.

`app/api/contact/route.ts`
Public contact form submission route.

How these work:
Frontend pages or admin forms can call these routes to read/write data.
Example:
- public notices page can fetch `/api/notices`
- contact form posts to `/api/contact`

**Inside `components/`**

We split this into two parts.

`components/site/`
Reusable public website components.

Files there:
- `header.tsx`  
  School header + top government strip + navigation

- `footer.tsx`  
  Footer with quick links and contact info

- `section.tsx`  
  Shared layout wrapper for page sections

- `cards.tsx`  
  Notice card, gallery card, and download card UIs

- `contact-form.tsx`  
  Frontend form that submits contact messages

- `page-hero.tsx`  
  Reusable top banner for internal pages like About, Contact, Admissions

`components/admin/`
Reusable admin UI components.

Files there:
- `login-form.tsx`  
  Admin login form using NextAuth credentials

- `shell.tsx`  
  Shared admin layout with sidebar and content area

**Inside `lib/`**

This folder contains the project’s shared logic.

`lib/types.ts`
TypeScript types/interfaces for data like:
- notices
- gallery items
- downloads
- homepage content
- site settings

This keeps the code safer and more consistent.

`lib/sample-data.ts`
Fallback sample content.
This is very useful because the website can still show UI even if MongoDB is not connected yet.

`lib/utils.ts`
Small utility helpers like:
- class merging
- date formatting

`lib/mongodb.ts`
MongoDB connection logic.
This connects the app to MongoDB Atlas and caches the connection so it isn’t recreated on every request.

`lib/youtube.ts`
Extracts YouTube video ID from different types of YouTube links.
Example:
- `youtube.com/watch?v=...`
- `youtu.be/...`

This is useful because we only want to store the video ID, not full messy links.

`lib/auth.ts`
NextAuth configuration.
Defines:
- credentials login
- session strategy
- admin username/password fallback from env vars

`lib/content.ts`
Data access layer.
This is important.

It tries to load data from MongoDB first, and if DB is not configured, it falls back to `sample-data.ts`.

So pages still work during early development.

`lib/api.ts`
Helper for protecting admin API routes.
Checks whether the user is logged in before allowing write actions.

**Inside `models/`**

Each file here defines one MongoDB collection structure.

`models/Notice.ts`
For:
- title
- Hindi title
- type
- description
- file URL
- event date
- pinned status

`models/GalleryItem.ts`
For:
- title
- photo/video type
- image URL
- YouTube ID
- category

`models/Download.ts`
For downloadable resources like:
- admission forms
- calendars
- circulars
- govt orders

`models/HomepageContent.ts`
Singleton content for homepage sections like:
- hero slides
- principal message
- achievements
- why choose us

`models/SiteSettings.ts`
Singleton settings for the whole site like:
- school name
- Hindi name
- address
- phone
- email
- map URL
- social links

`models/ContactSubmission.ts`
Stores contact form entries from users.

`models/Admin.ts`
Admin user schema.
Right now auth mainly uses env credentials, but this model is ready if you later want DB-based admin accounts.

**Inside `scripts/`**

`scripts/seed.ts`
Seeds the database with sample content.
This helps quickly populate MongoDB with demo notices, downloads, gallery items, homepage content, and settings.

**How Everything Connects**

The flow is:

- `app/` shows pages to users
- pages use `lib/content.ts` to fetch data
- `lib/content.ts` reads from MongoDB using `models/`
- if MongoDB is missing, it uses `lib/sample-data.ts`
- admin/API writes happen through `app/api/...`
- admin protection uses `lib/auth.ts` + `middleware.ts`

So the architecture is clean:

- `app` = routes/pages/API
- `components` = reusable UI
- `lib` = shared logic/helpers
- `models` = database structure
- `scripts` = developer utilities

